It&#x27;s only a surprise if you don&#x27;t understand it.  Every Perl programmer needs to fully grok and embrace it because it&#x27;s a core language feature.<p>For others, this is what <i>EdwardDiego</i> is referring to:<p><pre><code>  my %hash = (a => 1, b => 2, c => 3, d => 4);

  # list context (plural)
  my @keys = keys %hash;
  my ($key1, $key2, @rest_of_keys) = keys %hash;

  # scalar context (singular)
  my $number_of_keys = keys %hash;
  say scalar keys %hash;

  # An example of iterator usage
  my ($first_key, $first_value) = each %hash;
  my ($second_key, $second_value) = each %hash;

  # void context
  keys %hash;    # resets iterator</code></pre>
